========================================================================
DISABLE FALLOUT 4 VR FAVORITES MENU - INSTALLATION AND BUILD GUIDE
========================================================================

This document details how to fetch, configure, compile, and package this
plugin.

CRITICAL ARCHITECTURAL REQUIREMENT: VISUAL STUDIO (MSVC) ABI COMPLIANCE
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Fallout 4 VR and F4SEVR are compiled entirely using the Microsoft Visual
Studio C++ compiler (MSVC). C++ binaries compiled with different toolchains
(such as MinGW or GCC) use a completely incompatible Application Binary
Interface (ABI)—they mangle names differently and layout memory structures
differently.

Injecting a MinGW-compiled DLL into an MSVC-compiled game WILL cause
instant desktop crashes.

Therefore, you MUST use the MSVC toolchain to build this project. MinGW
and Clang-cl configurations are explicitly unsupported.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. PREREQUISITES
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Ensure the following tools are present in your Windows system environment:

* Git for Windows       (https://git-scm.com)
* CMake (Version 3.18+) (https://cmake.org/download/)

* Microsoft Visual C++ Compiler (MSVC x64 Build Tools):
  You do NOT need to install the heavy Visual Studio IDE. You can use the
  lightweight "Build Tools for Visual Studio" installer from Microsoft.

  During installation, check ONLY the following module workload:
  [X] Desktop development with C++

------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. CLONING AND SETUP
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Open your terminal or command prompt and clone the project files:

    git clone https://github.com/arifogel/DisableFallout4VRFavoritesMenu
    cd DisableFallout4VRFavoritesMenu

CMake will automatically download, extract, and map the remote F4SEVR
SDK dependencies from the official servers during the generation step.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. COMPILING THE PLUGIN
------------------------------------------------------------------------

You can build this project either through the command line or using a
modern IDE. Both methods are pre-configured to handle separate, isolated
build directories for Debug and Release targets.

CHOICE A: THE COMMAND LINE WAY (BULLETPROOF)
To configure your build workspace, open your terminal in the repository root.
You can completely omit explicit version generator strings; CMake will
automatically scan your Windows registry and use the highest generation of the
Microsoft Visual Studio toolchain you have locally installed.

You only need to explicitly specify the 64-bit runtime target architecture:

  1. Generate the workspace files:
         cmake -B build -A x64

  2. Compile your target profile:

     For a Debug target (unoptimized, full diagnostic symbols):
         cmake --build build --config Debug

     For a Release target (highly optimized for VR performance):
         cmake --build build --config Release


CHOICE B: THE IDE WAY (CLion / Visual Studio)
If you prefer developing inside an Integrated Development Environment:

  * If using JetBrains CLion (Highly Recommended):
    1. Select "Open" and choose the repository root folder.
    2. CLion will automatically parse the committed `.idea` metadata. It
       will instantly load your pre-configured MSVC x64 toolchain, pair
       it with Ninja, and populate your split Debug/Release profiles.
       No manual setup is required.

  * If using Visual Studio 2022:
    1. Select "Open a local folder" and choose the repository root.
    2. Visual Studio will automatically detect CMakeLists.txt and configure
       itself using the native MSVC x64 toolchain.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. CREATING THE 7Z MOD DISTRIBUTION PACKAGE
------------------------------------------------------------------------

To bundle the compiled Release binary and its accompanying PDB symbol file
(used by VR crash loggers) into a mod-manager-compliant archive, run the
native package target pipeline after your Release build finishes:

  * Via Command Line:
    Run the following command from the root directory:
        cmake --build build --config Release --target PACKAGE

  * Via CLion:
    Select the pre-configured `Package` build profile from the top-right
    dropdown menu and click the Build (Hammer) icon.

Once completed, your final package will be generated at:

    .\build\DisableFallout4VRFavoritesMenu-1.0.0-win64.7z
    (Or inside .\cmake-build-release\ if compiling via CLion Ninja)

This file contains the precise underlying structure (`F4SE/Plugins/`) and
is ready to be dropped straight into Mod Organizer 2 or Vortex.
========================================================================